DENSITY ESTIMATION¶

In Kanai, R., Feilden, T., Firth, C. and Rees, G., 2011. Political orientations are correlated with brain structure in young adults. Current biology, 21(8), pp.677-680., data are collected to study whether or not the two brain regions are likely to be independent of each other and considering di erent types of political view For this question; you can use the proper package for histogram and KDE; no need to write your own. The data set n90pol.csv contains information on 90 university students who participated in a psychological experiment designed to look for relationships between the size of di erent regions of the brain and political views. The variables amygdala and acc indicate the volume of two particular brain regions known to be involved in emotions and decision-making, the amygdala and the anterior cingulate cortex; more exactly, these are residuals from the predicted volume, after adjusting for height, sex, and similar body-type variables. The variable orientation gives the students' locations on a ve-point scale from 1 (very conservative) to 5 (very liberal). Note that in the dataset, we only have observations for orientation from 2 to 5.

Identifying Independence from conditional density and marginal density results¶

Looking roughly from the plots of joint distribution of amygdala and acc, and the individual distributions, we can observe that the peaks and data distribution seem similar for the joint distributions and marginal distributions.

If p(x) and p(y) represent the marginal distributions of 2 variables x and y, and p(x,y) represents their joint distribution, then we can state the two variables are independent if :
p(x,y) = p(x)p(y)
In other words, the difference between the density estimations for them should be close to 0. However, since we have errors associated with the density estimations of our dataset, we can identify some residuals in this difference. If the residuals are small, we could state that the variables are independent. Below were the steps followed to identify residuals and plot them
a) Using scipy.stats.gaussian_kde, get the marginal pdf’s for amygdala and acc using 0.3 as the bandwidth.
b) Using scipy.stats.gaussian_kde, get the joint pdf of amygdala and acc.
c) Identify the residuals using formula absolute(p(x,y) - p(x) p(y))
d) Plot the marginal distribution, join distribution and residuals to observe the residuals.
Below are the results.

909.7678892987302
8.248725631208412

The points with values less than 60 are marked in red and remaining in blue. We can observe that most of the residuals are red, which means that they have values close to 0, whilst the data points which represent the densities have values in the range of 100-300. From this, we can say that the residuals are close to 0 and this could be due to noise in the estimated densities. The sum of residuals comes to 2871. Also, the percentage of ratio of the average value of residuals to the average value of the joint distribution is around 8%.¶

We cannot confirm independence since we have residuals.¶

Conditional Distribution of amygdala on orientation¶

From the 4 plots of distributions of amygdala with the 4 types of brain orientations, we can observe that most of the data is observed around 0.00 for all 4 orientations. There is a slight difference for c=3, but it is not very significant. There is not much difference between the orientations from these plots. In other words, we cannot infer a difference between the brain structure and political view from these plots.¶
